### XCVIII. HOW A MAN SKILLED IN CELESTIAL MATTERS.

<span id="img_14500"></span> ![](img/14500.jpg)

When they would symbolise *a man skilled in celestial matters*, they
depict A CRANE FLYING;  <span id="fr_142"></span>[2](#fn_137.md) for she
always flies very high, to inspect the clouds lest they send forth a
storm, that she may remain in quiet. <span
id="fr_143"></span>[3](#fn_138.md)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Footnotes

<span id="fn_137"></span>[145:2](hh171.htm#fr_142.md)

*The Ibis denotes Thoth, who was the Egyptian inventor of astronomy*.

<span id="fn_138"></span>[145:3](hh171.htm#fr_143.md) Treb. hæc enim ita
alte advolat, ut nubes videat et tangat, "for it flies so high that it
inspects and touches the clouds."

